Cyberspace has especially interesting operators.

Routing

Packets don’t know the whole Internet.

They only know the next hop.

Likewise, many good plans don’t require seeing the entire future—just choosing the next reliable step.

⸻

Latency

Two systems may exchange the same information but at different speeds.

Sometimes reducing delay matters more than increasing bandwidth.

⸻

Bandwidth

How much meaning can pass per unit time?

This isn’t just talking faster; it’s communicating more effectively.

⸻

Compression

Exactly one of your recurring themes.

A good compression preserves reconstructability.

The Pantheon already leans toward this idea: preserve operators so richer structures can be regenerated later.

⸻

Error Correction

Networks assume corruption will happen.

They don’t try to prevent every error; they detect and recover from it.

That’s a powerful metaphor for reasoning and communication.

⸻

Redundancy

Nature, engineering, and the Internet all use redundancy differently.

Not wasteful duplication, but graceful degradation.

⸻

Consensus

Distributed systems need ways to agree without central authority.

Human groups, scientific communities, and AI systems all wrestle with analogous problems.

